text:
{
  "prompt": "A detailed 2D side view blueprint of an electric scooter with a skateboard-style frame. The front wheel is 20 inches, the rear wheel is 18 inches (asymmetrical setup). The frame is long and flat, housing a large battery under the footplate. The seat is wide and cushioned, positioned like on a Yamaha XMAX scooter. Rider foot position is slightly forward (relaxed touring position). The scooter has dual rear shock absorbers, front telescopic forks, and disk brakes on both wheels. Include detailed proportions and mechanical structure like swingarm, motor mount area, and head tube.",
  "size": "1024x1024"
}

{
  "prompt": "A concept 3D rendering of an electric scooter designed with a skateboard-style frame and aerodynamic structure. The scooter features a large 20-inch front wheel and a smaller 18-inch rear wheel, with a wheelbase of 1500mm. The frame includes a low, flat deck with a built-in 72V 100Ah battery compartment. It has a wide, cushioned seat similar in shape to the Yamaha XMAX for comfort during long rides. The front includes a large, adjustable windscreen with a two-stage vertical sliding mechanism. The overall design is sleek and streamlined, emphasizing airflow with smooth body lines, a low front profile, integrated front air channels, and a dual rear air shock system. The front fork is an air suspension unit, and the scooter features disc brakes with ABS and a visible TCS module. The 3D rendering is shown in high-resolution, side view, with clean lighting and no background, focused on design details.",
  "size": "1024x1024"
}

{
  "prompt": "A detailed 3D rendering of a modern electric scooter with its aerodynamic bodywork, cowls, and covers removed. The frame is fully exposed, showing the skateboard-style flat deck for the battery (72V 100Ah), front 20-inch wheel with air suspension fork and disc brake, rear 18-inch wheel with double air shocks, and central motor with chain drive. The front features a mounting bracket for a height-adjustable windscreen. The structure reveals the tubular frame, swingarm, suspension geometry, and electronic components. Designed for aerodynamic efficiency and comfort like the Yamaha XMAX.",
  "size": "1024x1024"
}
